text: Welcome to today's guided meditation. Over the last few sessions, we've practiced mindfully observing the breath. If you haven't had much experience meditating, you may find that it is surprisingly difficult to maintain your focus, especially in an environment with many distractions. If you're in a noisy place, why not try including these distractions during the session? Let the sounds come and go, just as you do with your thoughts. Notice them clearly, and observe any reactions you may have to them. Be aware as they arise, and then return to the breath. Or, if you like, you can even use the sounds of your environment as the focus of your meditation, instead of the breath. Pay close attention to every detail of sounds as they arise. Notice how you can't control them, nor can you control your ability to hear them. If you get distracted by thinking, take notice of the thought, and return to a careful, open awareness of the sounds around you. Let's try this in today's session. We'll be focusing on the sounds around us as we meditate today. As usual, take a seat with a straight back and arms resting on your legs. Close your eyes, and take some deep breaths. Try to release any tension in your body as you breathe out. Observe the sensations of your body as you sit, and the feeling of air entering and leaving your lungs. Set a clear intention in your mind for this session. Now, bring your attention to the sounds around you. Listen very carefully to each sound as it arises. Just let the sounds come and go. Be aware if you have any physical or emotional reactions to a particular sound. Observe them, and let them pass as you return to a clear awareness of the sounds around you.
